Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all produce.

Halve @green bell peppers{2} lengthwise; remove stems and seeds. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}. Finely dice @Roma tomato{1}.

Place bell peppers on a #baking sheet{} and drizzle each half with @olive oil{4%teaspoon}; rub to coat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Arrange cut sides down.

Roast on middle rack until browned and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tablespoon} in a large, preferably ovenproof, pan over medium-high heat. Add onion; cook, stirring, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from pan.

Add @ground plant-based protein{9%ounce} and @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon}; season generously with salt and pepper. Using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer; cook, without stirring, until browned on bottom, ~{3-4%minutes}. Break up protein into pieces and continue cooking until browned all over and warmed through, ~{3-4%minutes} more.

Return onion to pan; stir to combine.

Stir @tomato paste{1.5%ounce}, @veggie stock concentrate{2} and diced tomato into pan until thoroughly combined.

Add @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce} and 1 1/2 cups water (3 cups for 4 servings); season generously with salt and pepper. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium low. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until liquid is mostly absorbed and couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Turn off heat and stir in @butter{2%tablespoon} (4 TBSP for 4).

Once bell peppers are done, stuff each half with as much filling as will fit.

Place in pan with remaining filling, nestling each stuffed pepper into mixture.

> TIP: If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer mixture to a small baking dish and arrange stuffed pepper halves in there.

Evenly sprinkle stuffed peppers with @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup}.

Bake stuffed peppers on middle rack until cheese melts, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Divide remaining filling between plates, top with stuffed peppers, and serve.